const REPORT_DATA = {"patient_name":"Nicoleta Boroianu","dob":"07/12/1992","report_date":"2026-05-10","summary":"IMPORTANT: This report contains findings that we recommend discussing with your GP promptly. Please bring this report with you to your appointment. The specific items requiring medical attention are detailed in the Clinical Recommendations section below.\n\nNicoleta presents as a 33-year-old female with a BMI of 18.7, performing no resistance training and one cardio session per week with 2,000 to 5,000 daily steps. Her diet quality is rated 7 out of 10 but her food volume is just 3 out of 10. She reports sleeping less than 6 hours most nights and her symptoms are fatigue, brain fog, and joint pain/stiffness. Her goals are to improve gut health, reduce anxiety, and build muscle.\n\nThere are some genuinely positive findings in this profile. Her vitamin D at 101 is within the optimal range, her B12 at 585 and folate at 10 are both healthy, her inflammatory markers are excellent (hs-CRP 0.2, ESR 2), her kidney function is clean (eGFR 90+, Cystatin C 0.73), her liver enzymes are all within range, her digestive enzymes are normal, her triglycerides at 0.67 are excellent, her HDL at 2.0 provides strong cardiovascular protection, her immunoglobulins are balanced, her rheumatoid factor is negative (reassuring given joint pain), and her celiac screen is negative.\n\nHowever, several findings require attention, and the central theme of this report is that her body is not receiving enough fuel to function properly.\n\nThe most significant finding is clinical iron deficiency anemia. Her hemoglobin at 101 g/L is significantly below the normal range of 120 to 150. This is not a borderline or suboptimal result; hemoglobin at this level means her blood does not have enough healthy red blood cells to deliver adequate oxygen to her tissues, muscles, and brain. This is very likely the primary driver of her fatigue and brain fog. Her ferritin at 9 is below the normal range (10 to 291), meaning her iron stores are essentially empty. Her RDW at 19.1 is very significantly above the normal range (11.6 to 14), indicating her bone marrow is producing red blood cells of highly inconsistent sizes because iron availability is fluctuating. Her hematocrit at 0.287 and red blood cell count at 3.32 are both well below their respective ranges. Her reticulocyte absolute count at 29 is below the normal range (50 to 100), confirming her bone marrow is underproducing new red blood cells because it does not have the iron to make them. Her transferrin saturation at 18.2% is sitting right at the lower boundary. This picture requires GP assessment, as oral iron supplements alone may not be sufficient at this level of depletion, and her GP may wish to consider IV iron or investigate whether there is an underlying cause of blood loss such as heavy periods or gastrointestinal bleeding.\n\nHer urine culture grew a heavy amount of Enterococcus bacteria, indicating a urinary tract infection that requires antibiotic treatment. The laboratory tested which antibiotics this bacteria responds to and found it is sensitive to nitrofurantoin, ampicillin, cefalexin, augmentin, ciprofloxacin, and amoxicillin. Importantly, it is resistant to trimethoprim and mecillinam, which are commonly prescribed first-line antibiotics for UTIs, so these would not be effective. This finding should be discussed with her GP. An active infection, even one she may not be feeling obvious symptoms from, can contribute to fatigue and general unwellness.\n\nHer Lipoprotein(a) at 161.72 nmol/L is very significantly elevated, more than five times the upper limit of 32. Lipoprotein(a) is a genetically determined particle that cannot be changed by diet, exercise, or lifestyle. It is inherited and is an independent risk factor for cardiovascular disease. This is not caused by anything she has done, it is simply a genetic variation that affects approximately 20% of the population to varying degrees. This finding should be permanently recorded on her medical notes, and her GP should be made aware of it. Some of her elevated LDL (3.84) and ApoB (1.08) readings are likely attributable to Lp(a), as the standard cholesterol tests include Lp(a) particles in the LDL count.\n\nMultiple markers point to her body being in a state of significant undernutrition. At BMI 18.7 with a food volume of 3 out of 10, she is not consuming enough calories to support basic body functions. Her insulin at 1.97 is below the normal range, her C-Peptide at 129.8 pmol/L is below range, and her HOMA-IR at 0.39 is below range. While low insulin is normally protective, being below the normal range in this context reflects a body that has reduced insulin production because so little glucose is entering the bloodstream. Her creatinine at 44 is below the normal range (49 to 90) and her myoglobin at 17.93 is below range (25 to 72), both reflecting very low muscle mass. Her alkaline phosphatase at 37 is below the normal range (46 to 116), which is commonly associated with malnutrition and zinc deficiency. Her uric acid at 135 is below the normal range (184 to 464), reflecting very low protein intake. Her leptin at 2.8 is below the optimal range, confirming very low body fat reserves and signalling to the brain that energy availability is critically limited.\n\nHer cortisol at 143 is below the standard morning reference range of 172 to 497. However, cortisol follows a natural daily rhythm and drops significantly throughout the day, so if this blood was drawn in the afternoon, a reading of 143 may be within the expected range. Her DHEA-S at 663 \u00b5g/L is within the normal range but below optimal. Both chronic sleep restriction (under 6 hours) and insufficient caloric intake can suppress adrenal hormone production over time, which may be contributing to her fatigue and anxiety.\n\nHer thyroid function shows FT4 at 12, sitting just above the lower boundary of 11.5. Her TSH at 2.58 is within range but