 without requiring large meals. Prioritising iron-rich foods like red meat, lentils, dark leafy greens, eggs, and fortified cereals would directly support the anemia recovery alongside any treatment your GP recommends.\n\nYour sleep of less than 6 hours most nights is the other major factor. Sleep is when the body repairs tissues (relevant to your joint pain), regulates hormones (relevant to your cortisol and anxiety), consolidates memory and focus (relevant to your brain fog), and supports immune function. Chronic sleep restriction under 6 hours impairs all of these processes. Even increasing from 5 to 6.5 or 7 hours would produce measurable improvements. If difficulty sleeping is the issue rather than lifestyle choice, this is worth discussing with your GP.\n\nYour goal of building muscle is entirely achievable but requires two things your body currently does not have: adequate caloric intake (particularly protein at 1.2 to 1.6g per kilogram bodyweight) and resistance training. Starting with two light resistance sessions per week alongside gradually increasing food volume would be a sustainable starting point. Your body cannot build tissue if it does not have the raw materials to build with.","flags":"\u2022 Hemoglobin at 101 g/L (normal 120 to 150) with ferritin at 9 (below range), RDW at 19.1 (very significantly above range), hematocrit at 0.287 (below range), RBC at 3.32 (below range), and reticulocyte absolute at 29 (below range). Clinical iron deficiency anemia that requires GP assessment. Very likely the primary driver of fatigue and brain fog.\n\n\u2022 Urine culture grew heavy Enterococcus sp., a bacterial urinary tract infection requiring antibiotic treatment. Resistant to trimethoprim and mecillinam. Sensitive to nitrofurantoin, ampicillin, cefalexin, augmentin, ciprofloxacin, and amoxicillin. Requires GP assessment.\n\n\u2022 Lipoprotein(a) at 161.72 nmol/L, more than five times the upper limit of 32. This is a genetic cardiovascular risk factor that cannot be changed by lifestyle and should be permanently recorded on medical notes.\n\n\u2022 Multiple markers of undernutrition: insulin 1.97 (below range), C-Peptide 129.8 (below range), HOMA-IR 0.39 (below range), creatinine 44 (below range reflecting very low muscle mass), myoglobin 17.93 (below range), ALP 37 (below range reflecting malnutrition), uric acid 135 (below range reflecting low protein intake). Collectively these reflect a body not receiving sufficient caloric intake.\n\n\u2022 Cortisol at 143 is below the standard morning reference range (172 to 497). If blood was drawn in the morning, this may reflect reduced adrenal output from chronic caloric restriction and sleep deprivation.\n\n\u2022 FT4 at 12 sitting just above the lower boundary (11.5) with TPO antibodies at 13 borderline (limit 13.8). Worth monitoring at follow-up.\n\n\u2022 LDL at 3.84 and ApoB at 1.08 are above range, but partly attributable to the very high Lipoprotein(a) which is included in these measurements.","recommendations":"We recommend booking an appointment with your GP promptly and bringing this report. There are three findings that require medical attention:\n\n1. Your hemoglobin at 101 with ferritin at 9 indicates clinical iron deficiency anemia. Your GP will likely want to confirm this with a repeat blood count and may consider whether oral iron supplementation is sufficient or whether IV iron infusion would be more appropriate given the severity. Your GP should also investigate whether there is a cause of blood loss contributing, such as heavy menstrual periods or gastrointestinal bleeding, as this level of anemia at 33 warrants understanding the underlying cause.\n\n2. Your urine culture grew heavy Enterococcus bacteria that requires antibiotic treatment. Importantly, the laboratory found this bacteria is resistant to trimethoprim and mecillinam (commonly prescribed UTI antibiotics), so your GP will need to prescribe an alternative such as nitrofurantoin, ampicillin, or cefalexin based on the sensitivities provided.\n\n3. Your Lipoprotein(a) at 161.72 is a significant genetic cardiovascular risk factor that should be permanently recorded on your medical notes. Your GP should be aware of this finding for long-term cardiovascular risk management. Some of your elevated LDL and ApoB readings are likely Lp(a)-associated and cannot be modified by lifestyle.\n\nYour borderline TPO antibodies at 13 (limit 13.8) and low-end FT4 at 12 should be monitored at your 12-week follow-up to check for any thyroid changes.\n\nA follow-up blood test in 12 weeks focusing on full blood count, ferritin, transferrin saturation, reticulocytes, TSH, FT4, TPO antibodies, cortisol (morning fasting), and PTH is strongly recommended.","supplementation":"IMPORTANT: Your anemia is significant enough that supplementation decisions should be guided by your GP. The following suggestions are intended to complement, not replace, whatever treatment plan your GP recommends.\n\nIf your GP advises oral iron supplementation, iron bisglycinate at 25 to 30mg every other day taken on an empty stomach with vitamin C would be the gentlest effective approach. Every-other-day dosing has been shown to improve absorption compared to daily. However, at hemoglobin 101 and ferritin 9, your GP may recommend a higher dose or IV iron instead, and their recommendation should take priority.\n\nMagnesium glycinate at 300 to 400mg before bed may support sleep quality, anxiety, joint health, and energy production. Sleep restriction under 6 hours depletes magnesium, and supplementation commonly helps with both sleep onset and sleep quality.\n\nVitamin C at 500 to 1,000mg daily would support iron absorption (critical given the anemia), immune function, and connective tissue repair relevant to the joint pain.\n\nZinc at 15mg daily as zinc picolinate may help address the below-range ALP (37) which can indicate zinc deficiency. Zinc also supports immune function and tissue repair. Zinc and vitamin C require specialised testing not available in our current offering.\n\nCollagen peptides at 10 to 15g daily, ideally taken with vitamin C 30 to 60 minutes before any physical activity, may support joint cartilage and connective tissue repair, which is relevant to joint pain in the context of low muscle mass and undernutrition.\n\nMaintain your current vitamin D supplementation or intake, as your level at 101 is excellent and should be sustained.\n\nAvoid taking iron and zinc at the same time as they compete for absorption. Space them at least 2 hours apart.\n\nA high-quality multivitamin with minerals may provide broad nutritional support given the undernutrition picture, but this should not replace adequate caloric intake. Supplements cannot substitute for food.","biomarkers":[{"key":"albumin","name":"Albumin","group":"LIVER & METABOLIC","result":"40","within_normal":"TRUE","within_optimal":"TRUE","result_position":"0.4583","lower_normal":"34","upper_normal":"50","lower_optimal":"40","upper_optimal":"48","lower_normal_position":"0.3333","upper_normal_position":"0.6667","lower_optimal_position":"0.4583","upper_optimal_position":"0.625","units":"g/L","description":"Primary protein made by liver","low_causes":"Liver disease, kidney disease, inflammation, malnutrition","high_causes":"Dehydration","padding":"1","one_sided":"0.5","range_type":"normal"},{"key":"alt","name":"ALT","group":"LIVER & METABOLIC","result":"16","within_normal":"TRUE","within_optimal":"TRUE","result_position":"0.3946","lower_normal":"7","upper_normal":"56","lower_optimal":"7","upper_optimal":"20","lower_normal_position":"0.3333","upper_normal_position":"0.6667","lower_optimal_position":"0.3333","upper_optimal_position":"0.4218","units":"U/L","description":"Liver enzyme released when liver cells are damaged. Within range","low_causes":"Rarely clinically significant","high_causes":"Hepatitis, fatty liver, alcohol, medications","padding":"1","one_sided":"0.5","range_type":"normal"},{"key":"alkalinephos